    <fr:title text="Forester 4.2 › new query language › unions and intersections of families of queries › querying all hereditary contributors to a tree"><fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00X1.xml" title="Forester 4.2 › new query language › unions and intersections of families of queries" addr="//forester/jms-00X1" type="local"><fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00WS.xml" title="Forester 4.2 › new query language" addr="//forester/jms-00WS" type="local"><fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00WK.xml" title="Forester 4.2" addr="//forester/jms-00WK" type="local">Forester 4.2</fr:link> › new query language</fr:link> › unions and intersections of families of queries</fr:link> › querying all hereditary contributors to a tree</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>We can use the union of families of relational queries to compute the set of (proper) <fr:link href="foreign-forester-tfmt-000T.xml" title="Contributor to a tree" addr="//forester/tfmt-000T" type="local"><fr:em>contributors</fr:em></fr:link> to a given tree. This is slightly subtle, because if a bibliographic tree is transcluded, we do not want its contributors to be included.</fr:p>
    <fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\query/contributors[x]{
 \open\query
 \union-fam-rel{
  \isect{
   \transclusion-coslice{\x}
  }{
   \compl{
    \taxon{reference}
   }
  }
 }{\edges}{\outgoing}{\rel/contributors}
}]]></fr:pre>
  </fr:mainmatter>
